ms of a functionally differentiated world society and argue that they are completely novel because they incessantly adapt to the process of functional differentiation. To this end, they define structural core characteristics of modern policy, such as the political inclusion of everyone as a reaction to individualism; the complexity of polities arising from internal differentiation; and the increasing political decision-making handed to experts and autonomous organizations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPolitical science. 4aAutocracy. 4aDemocracy. 4aFunctional Autonomy. 4aGlobalization. 4aInternal Differentiation. 4aKnowledge. 4aPolitical Sociology. 4aPolitics. 4aResponsiveness. 4aSociety. 4aSociological Theory. 4aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAutocracy.  aDemocracy.  aFunctional Autonomy.  aGlobalization.  aInternal Differentiation.  aKnowledge.  aPolitical Sociology.  aPolitics.  aResponsiveness.  aSociety.  aSociological Theory.  aSociology.1 aAhlers, Anna L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrichewsky, Damien, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKrichewsky, Damien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoser, Evelyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMoser, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStichweh, Rudolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook p